 Wednesday, April 21, 2004 				 Guinness co-founder is dead
																								London, April 20 (Reuters): Norris McWhirter, who founded Guinness World Records with his twin brother and turned the book into a global bestseller, has died aged 78, a spokesman said today.																								McWhirter suffered a heart attack yesterday after playing tennis at his home in southwest England, the spokesman said.																								The London-born son of a newspaper director, McWhirter was a writer, sports commentator and athlete but will best be remembered for co-founding the Guinness Book of Records  now known as Guinness World Records  in 1955. Ross was assassinated by the IRA in 1975 for his opinions on the situation in Northern Ireland.
